[
    {
        "content": "<p>Is there a way to state as a Prop that, it is the case that x : T?</p>",
        "id": 467067026,
        "sender_full_name": "nrs",
        "timestamp": 1725320166
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I believe no, not directly. Can you share what you're going to do with that prop?</p>",
        "id": 467067772,
        "sender_full_name": "Julian Berman",
        "timestamp": 1725320614
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"321696\">Julian Berman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/Is.20there.20a.20proposition.20stating.20x.20.3A.20T.3F/near/467067772\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I believe no, not directly. Can you share what you're going to do with that prop?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I was thinking we could use that hypothesis to prove universally quantified statements. I know the usual way in Lean is to rewrite the goal and then use intro, but a previous formal system I used had semantics for introducing the hypothesis that x : T to roughly emulate \"let x be some element of T\" (introduced as a hypothesis in case T is empty) and I was wondering whether such a thing was possible in Lean</p>",
        "id": 467068275,
        "sender_full_name": "nrs",
        "timestamp": 1725320873
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(for reference, it's the system stated here and the <code>\\forall sub</code> rule specifically: <a href=\"https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/1681857/predicate-logic-how-do-you-self-check-the-logical-structure-of-your-own-argumen\">https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/1681857/predicate-logic-how-do-you-self-check-the-logical-structure-of-your-own-argumen</a>, but it's not at all a type-level thing. I was just looking to emulate a pattern of thought I had while using it. This reference not necessary for context but just in case)</p>",
        "id": 467068467,
        "sender_full_name": "nrs",
        "timestamp": 1725321000
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Nonempty.elim#doc\">docs#Nonempty.elim</a> it looks like  -- not sure if that's helpful to point you to.</p>",
        "id": 467083552,
        "sender_full_name": "Julian Berman",
        "timestamp": 1725327837
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"321696\">Julian Berman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/Is.20there.20a.20proposition.20stating.20x.20.3A.20T.3F/near/467083552\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>There's <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Nonempty.elim#doc\">docs#Nonempty.elim</a> it looks like  -- not sure if that's helpful to point you to.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I'll be investigating it, thanks!</p>",
        "id": 467086378,
        "sender_full_name": "nrs",
        "timestamp": 1725329077
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think \"declaring a forall type and then using intro\", declaring a function type and working in its body, is not just the usual way but in some sense the <em>canonical</em> way of doing this in Lean's type theory</p>",
        "id": 467090761,
        "sender_full_name": "Robert Maxton",
        "timestamp": 1725330846
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or like, in the propositions-as-some-types framework, prop-level functions are precisely implications, and sort-level functions are methods of creating data assuming you have been given data.</p>",
        "id": 467090914,
        "sender_full_name": "Robert Maxton",
        "timestamp": 1725330930
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"359992\">Robert Maxton</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/Is.20there.20a.20proposition.20stating.20x.20.3A.20T.3F/near/467090761\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>There is a specific way to represent this concept and it is precisely by defining a function type and working in its body -- that is, by declaring a forall type and then using intro.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Oh, I think I get it how to do it without tactics (I think it's covered in Theorem Proving with Lean), but would there by a way to open a function body within tactics? for example, how would you begin such a function body within the following?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">apply</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Iff</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">intro</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">\\.</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">intro</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span>\n<span class=\"w\">   </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">how</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">would</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">I</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">throw</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">here</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">...?</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 467091457,
        "sender_full_name": "nrs",
        "timestamp": 1725331166
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>ah, using Julian's suggestion, we can achieve a similar behaviour by using a <code>{\\alpha : Type} [Nonempty \\alpha]</code> on the theorem, with <code>have x := Classical.choice (by assumption)</code></p>",
        "id": 467092385,
        "sender_full_name": "nrs",
        "timestamp": 1725331503
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>OH! You can just do:<br>\n<code>let hb := fun x : T =&gt; ...</code></p>",
        "id": 467102515,
        "sender_full_name": "nrs",
        "timestamp": 1725335320
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So e.g. we can do:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∧</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∧</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">apply</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Iff</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">intro</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">·</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">intro</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">l</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">specialize</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"bp\">;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">exact</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">left</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">r</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">specialize</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"bp\">;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">exact</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">right</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">apply</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">And</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">intro</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">l</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 467103629,
        "sender_full_name": "nrs",
        "timestamp": 1725335739
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>is there a way to make this form of proof a bit more concise?<br>\nedit: maybe</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">apply</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">And</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">intro</span>\n<span class=\"n\">exact</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">specialize</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"bp\">;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">exact</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">left</span>\n<span class=\"n\">exact</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">specialize</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"bp\">;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">exact</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">right</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 467103757,
        "sender_full_name": "nrs",
        "timestamp": 1725335778
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>rather than going into tactic mode in the lambda body (i.e. using <code>by [tactics]</code>, you can use <code>(h x).left</code> and <code>(h x).right</code></p>",
        "id": 467163670,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1725350207
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if you want it in maximally unreadable form:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Prop</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∧</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∧</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">∀</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↦</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">·|&gt;.</span><span class=\"m\">1</span><span class=\"o\">),</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">·|&gt;.</span><span class=\"m\">2</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">⟩</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↦</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"m\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"m\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"bp\">⟩⟩</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 467172241,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Rodriguez",
        "timestamp": 1725352365
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>small explanation: the <code>⟨⟩</code> are \"anonymous constructors\" (they do the <code>And</code>/<code>Iff.intro</code>), the dots basically hide a lambda abstraction (<code>fun x =&gt; (h x).1</code> for the first one, for example) and the <code>|&gt;</code> gets rid of brackets (it's needed here due to the semantics of the dot)</p>",
        "id": 467172610,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Rodriguez",
        "timestamp": 1725352457
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thank you very much for the help!! These are super cool!</p>",
